===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro}} {{term|corage|lang=fro}} (French: ''[[courage#French|courage]]''), from {{etyl|la}} {{term|cor||heart|lang=la}}. Distantly related to {{term|cardiac||of the heart|lang=en}}, which is from Greek, but from the same Proto-Indo-European root.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈkʌɹɪdʒ/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈkɝɪdʒ/}}
** {{audio|en-us-courage.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-}}

# The quality of a [[confident]] [[character]] not to be [[afraid]] or [[intimidate]]d [[easy|easily]] but without being [[incautious]] or [[inconsiderate]].
#: ''"A great part of '''courage''' is the courage of having done the thing before."'' —[[w:Ralph Waldo Emerson|Ralph Waldo Emerson]]
#: ''It takes a lot of '''courage''' to be successful in business.''
# The ability to do things which one finds frightening.
#: ''"'''Courage''' is not the absence of fear. It is acting in spite of it."'' —[[w:Mark Twain|Mark Twain]]
#: ''He plucked up the '''courage''' to tell her how he felt.''

